What we're going to do is we're going to do a progression. So get some chalk on your hands.

00:00:12.020 --> 00:00:18.100
So the great thing about the CrossFit program, you guys, is that it's infinitely scalable.

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:24.180
You can take someone like Scott who's winning TV shows and dominating local competitions, same thing with

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:27.220
Sheriff Lott, or you can take someone that's never climbed a rope before

00:00:27.220 --> 00:00:31.540
and give them a great stimuli. This is called the no-leg rope climb.

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:35.540
So her legs are never going to leave the ground, it's super safe,

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:39.160
but she gets the stimuli of the rope climb so here's how we're going to start.

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:45.380
You're just going to sit with the rope between your legs and you're going to use your legs just like on that jumping pull-up.

00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:48.940
And I just want you to climb hand over hand while using your legs.

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:52.640
So it looks like this—you're going to climb but you're going to stand at the same time.

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:56.480
So using your legs and using your arms—great big pulls.

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:09.020
Good. Now, she executed that like a true deputy sheriff.

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:13.400
Because she did it the harder way. Did you guys see the difference between the way I did it and the way she did it?

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:16.520
Her legs were straight. So that's actually the next progression.

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:21.740
What I did was I had a bent leg, which is easiest,

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:25.320
she's like, "Nah, it's too easy for me." She went straight-legged

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:28.780
and she also leaned back, which makes it even more difficult.

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:33.300
So that's outstanding. Do one more of those.

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:36.160
Then we'll see if we can get her off the ground.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:38.000
Student: Good luck with that one!

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:45.240
Great job, great job. Now, you guys see that range of motion?

00:01:45.240 --> 00:01:50.400
If you were going to pull me and get behind me to handcuff me, how are you going to grab my arm?

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:56.220
What's that hand going to do? Student: It's going to come over here. You see that range of motion she just did?

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:00.240
That grip is no different than the grip she took on the rope.

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:05.580
